	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-254154">

		
		<div class="comment-header">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/aaaba45be2fb2d4e14f79bb53f36661a?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />				<cite class="fn"><a href='http://emliterary.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Erin Murphy</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		 	</div>

			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
				<a href="http://www.slj.com/2014/05/diversity/an-expanded-cultural-diversity-booklist-slj-readers-respond/#comment-254154">May 13, 2014 at 3:54 pm</a>
							</div>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Susan Vaught&#8217;s TRIGGER follows a boy with traumatic brain injury; MY BIG FAT MANIFESTO is about a fat girl who refuses to conform; FREAKS LIKE US is about kids who are friends from the special education program at school; STORMWITCH features a Haitian immigrant at the time of Hurricane Camille; and the two OATHBREAKER books feature multiracial casts in a high fantasy setting.</p>
<p>Laura Resau&#8217;s THE QUEEN OF WATER and RED GLASS feature kids growing up in Latin America; STAR IN THE FOREST is about an illegal immigrant family; WHAT THE MOON SAW has an American girl learning the stories and traditions of the Mexican side of her family during one summer south of the American border.</p>
<p>Mike Jung&#8217;s GEEKS, GIRLS, AND SECRET IDENTITIES is a fast-paced superhero story with an Asian-American protagonist; Olugbemisola Rhuday-Perkovich&#8217;s EIGHTH-GRADE SUPERZERO features contemporary Brooklyn kids whose families are Caribbean; Natalie Dias Lorenzi&#8217;s FLYING THE DRAGON shows two sides of being Japanese-American; Trent Reedy&#8217;s WORDS IN THE DUST is set in recent Afghanistan.</p>
<p>e.E. Charlton Trujillo&#8217;s books all feature underrepresented populations; FAT ANGIE, her latest, not only embraces body image outside culturally prescribed zones; it also includes a romance between two girls.</p>
<p>Melanie Turner-Denstaedt&#8217;s THE HAT THAT WORE CLARA B. is a picture book about Mother&#8217;s Sunday, a tradition common in Black churches. Kelly Bennett&#8217;s picture book NOT NORMAN happens to have a boy of color as the protagonist of a simple story about wanting a pet. Liz Garton Scanlon&#8217;s ALL THE WORLD and Mary Lyn Ray&#8217;s STARS both feature large, diverse communities in Marla Frazee&#8217;s illustrations, and Liz&#8217;s infectious THINK BIG  also has a diverse cast of characters, and Mary Lyn&#8217;s new DEER DANCER features a brown girl who takes ballet class with a diverse group of students, including a boy. </p>
<p>More coming soon: Corinne Duyvis&#8217;s OTHERBOUND was praised by Kirkus for &#8220;convincing nonheteronormative relationships, balanced class issues, and nuanced, ethnically diverse characters.&#8221;</p>
<p>Stopping myself now before I hog all the comment space!</p>
		</div>

		<div class="reply">
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/05/diversity/an-expanded-cultural-diversity-booklist-slj-readers-respond/?replytocom=254154#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-254154", "254154", "respond", "96260")'>Reply</a>		</div>

		</li><!-- #comment-## -->

