	<li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="comment-256554">

		
		<div class="comment-header">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/b36bf99e297d7c4462f5f7f1256ee629?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />				<cite class="fn">Nicole Geiger</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		 	</div>

			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
				<a href="http://www.slj.com/2014/05/diversity/an-expanded-cultural-diversity-booklist-slj-readers-respond/#comment-256554">May 15, 2014 at 2:40 pm</a>
							</div>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Here&#8217;s a shout out to some older titles that are still available and deserve a mention: The Ezra Jack Keats award-winning picture book, YESTERDAY I HAD THE BLUES, by Jeron Ashford Frame and R. Gregory Christie, is a good addition to this list, and features an African American boy and his family. Also, Carmen Tafolla&#8217;s two picture books, WHAT CAN YOU DO WITH A REBOZO? and WHAT CAN YOU DO WITH A PALETA? feature Latino characters and cultural traditions.  Also, Monica Brown &amp; John Parra&#8217;s WAITING FOR THE BIBLIOBURRO focuses on Columbia&#8217;s famous traveling library. KING AND KING by Linda de Haan and Stern Nijland was the first picture book in the US to feature same-sex marriage. Last, Leslea Newman&#8217;s MOMMY, MAMA AND ME and DADDY, PAPA, AND ME are board books that feature same-sex parents. </p>
<p>All of these titles are available from Random House Children&#8217;s Books, and were initially published by Berkeley&#8217;s now-defunct Tricycle Press. Historically it&#8217;s been the smaller indie publishers who&#8217;ve led the charge but publisher survival isn&#8217;t assured. First Book&#8217;s announcement is a game-changer, and I hope that start-ups like Oakland&#8217;s Dream On Publishing will have a solid chance to thrive in the (hopefully) changing marketplace.</p>
		</div>

