	<li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="comment-257768">

		
		<div class="comment-header">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/3ef1fbb30a14b77a7d728b60aff2ae81?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />				<cite class="fn">Sheila Kelly Welch</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		 	</div>

			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
				<a href="http://www.slj.com/2014/05/diversity/an-expanded-cultural-diversity-booklist-slj-readers-respond/#comment-257768">May 16, 2014 at 3:29 pm</a>
							</div>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>I read with interest the article titled &#8220;How Cross Racial Scenes in Picture Books Build Acceptance&#8221; that was written by Krista Aronson and Anne O&#8217;Brien and published in  SLJ.  It&#8217;s good to see that research has been done that supports the assertion that multi-racial picture books &#8212; of a certain content &#8212; can help children become more accepting.  Positive attitudes were demonstrated by children&#8217;s willingness to play with others who were not of the same racial group. The books that actually caused this to happen  were ones in which there were illustrations depicting positive interactions between and among children who were not the same racial/ethnic background.  For those who haven&#8217;t seen this article, here&#8217;s a link:  </p>
<p><a href="http://www.slj.com/2014/05/diversity/how-cross-racial-scenes-in-picture-books-build-acceptance/article" rel="nofollow">http://www.slj.com/2014/05/diversity/how-cross-racial-scenes-in-picture-books-build-acceptance/article</a> </p>
<p>And here&#8217;s a book that is worth adding to this list as well as to the one that the researchers used. It&#8217;s called MOVING DAY  by Leone Castell Anderson and was originally titled THE GOOD-BY DAY.</p>
		</div>

